The sixth and final challenge of #projectquilting is posted! This week @quiltchicken is asking us to "Conquer a Fear"!

You see, to grow you must face fears. It’s the way to achieve and succeed. If you only do what’s safe and comfy, you’ll stagnate and grow soft.
 The way forward is always by finding and following a new path. Growth.
 
So this week, you will confront something you fear. Your project must be about growing through exploring the unknown.
 
What?
 
Well, first sit down and ponder your way forward: personally, professionally, creatively, emotionally, or quite literally physically moving forward in time and space. Where are you going? What do you need to overcome on the way?
 
Now, decide: how do I make that a quilt?
 
Here are some ideas:
• Are you thinking about changing careers? Going back to school? Does that feel more like a Delectable Mountain (#ad) to climb or you’re worried it’s just Robbing Peter to Pay Paul?
• Perhaps the holidays (pick one!) have been hard for you, but you’re ready to reclaim them with a fresh tree skirt for next year’s Christmas tree, or a seasonal topper for the table.
• Or perhaps you’ve been avoiding curved piecing or hand sewing or bias edges since you began quilting and it’s finally time to kick that anxiety to the curb?
 
Hopefully this will be a fun, freeing, liberating project in the end – although you may have moments of frustration or emotion along the way. Just remember, you can do it!!
 
Rule 1 – your project must involve conquering something that scares you.

Head to my blog #linkinbio to find out all the details for the challenge! I can't wait to see what everyone comes up with this week!

#travellog Wisconsin ✈️ Hawaii (Kauai)

Over the next few days (possibly 10) I’ll be sharing with you all about my families adventures in Kauai! We’re home now and it was amazing!! I’ll sprinkle in quilt posts here and there too when I can.

Day 1-2: woke up at 3:30am and flew out of Madison at 6:30 am. Arrived in Chicago no problem. While waiting to board our next flight we ran into my cousin John and his wife Angela! They were heading to Kauai too! Board the plane, start moving and then stop. A warning light went off and the pilots said it needed to be reset. They reset it, went off again, turns out there was a broken cable!

Needless to say, we missed our connecting flight from Phoenix to Lihue. The airline figured out a new option - we switched airlines, headed to LAX instead. They got us a hotel for the night and flew to Kauai the next day. One of our bags was lost overnight but somehow miraculously still arrived in Lihue 😍 bonus- we got to spend some time with John and Angela in the airport/hotel which made the delay so much better than it could have been. 

Arrived to some nice weather. Visited the beach near our hotel, ate, found @skinny_mikes (which we visited daily) and did a quick trip to Target! We made it!!!

#wiscogirltravels #wiscotohawaii #family #mylife #travel

Our first full day in Kauai was a bit overcast and rainy. We decide to drive west and see what we could find. We spent some time at the Salt Pond Beach park - it was the only place on Kauai not raining in the morning! Once the rain started at our beach though we headed to Hannapepe to check our shops and the swinging bridge. After we were done exploring we just chilled and caught up on some of our jet lag sleep. 
.
#wisconsintohawaii #wiscogirlinhawaii #kauai #saltpondbeach #hanapepe #vacation #myfamily #lifeofawisconsingirl

Day 2 in Kauai

Here’s my next “leaders-Enders” project! If you don’t know what leaders-Enders are it’s when you always start and end sewing on your machine with something random. This eliminates having to cut your thread all the time and also helps your real project from getting sucked into the machine. I learned about it from @quiltville_bonnie so be sure to check her out if I’ve confused you more! Leader-Enders can just be random scraps or you can make it a project that your not in a rush to finish. I’ve decided to make these fun scrappy quarter log cabin blocks. I have no plan on the finished quilt as far as size, layout , color … I’m just going to keep making until i feel like I have enough to put up on the design wall to play.

Happy Tuesday everyone! It's time for Kim (@gogokim) and I to share our next Plaidberry Quilt Block (pattern by @kindredquiltco ) ! I would like to take a minute to thank everyone for all their kind comments and support of the block I posted last week! It's been fun to read through everything and see how many eyes it caught.

When you visit @gogokim you'll see that she decided to change up her fabric choices. There is absolutely nothing wrong with that. As I told her - I loved her first block but if it wasn't making HER happy then she should switch it up. My biggest advice to anyone making a quilt or basically art of any kind is to make sure what you're doing makes you happy. If you've done that, that's all that matters.

I stuck with Tilda fabrics and my background is a fun ombre (in the metallic accent) of snippets II from @studio_e_fabrics . Definitely a more mellow reading quilt for me but I know exactly the person I’m gifting it to and she’s going to love it! I'll admit, I made my first Tilda fabric block just to try out the pattern and get a feel for it. After that, I switch up my fabric plans into something more my typical style. After making two blocks, I knew I had to continue with the quilt in the Tilda prints - it just called to me more. You can see my other attempt in the third picture.

If you'd want to make this quilt along with me and Kim you can purchase this pattern from @kindredquiltco in her Etsy shop! (I have a link in my bio to make it easy to find too!)

The final section of my #plaidberryblock quilt is complete! By sewing the blocks into four sections I minimize my longest seam to sew. If I had five strips I’d have to sew five really long seams. These four sections give me a two block seam, a three block seam and then one single five block seam. So much more manageable for me and a lot less chance to mess things up.
